{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614853"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16374"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16374"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.7,0.07,0.11,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74625"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9065"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60119"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"},{"type":"tags","id":"10336"},{"type":"tags","id":"10350"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21550"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21553"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74625"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathways provides motor output through the brainstem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dorsal column pathway","Corticospinal tract","Anterolateral pathway","Spinothalamic tract","Posterior column-medial lemniscus pathway"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brainstem contains multiple ascending and descending pathways that connect the brain with the spinal cord. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary motor pathway, carrying signals from the motor cortex through the brainstem to the spinal cord motor neurones that control voluntary movement. It descends through the ventral portion of the pons and forms the medullary pyramids before decussating (crossing over) at the pyramidal decussation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal column pathway\u003C/strong\u003E is an ascending sensory pathway that carries fine touch, vibration and proprioception information from the body to the brain. It does not carry motor signals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterolateral pathway\u003C/strong\u003E is another ascending sensory pathway that carries pain, temperature and crude touch information. It is not involved in motor function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espinothalamic tract\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the anterolateral system and carries pain and temperature sensation. It is a purely sensory pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior column-medial lemniscus pathway\u003C/strong\u003E is the same as the dorsal column pathway, carrying fine touch and proprioception. It does not provide motor output.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these pathways is crucial for localising neurological lesions. Damage to the corticospinal tract in the brainstem can cause weakness or paralysis below the level of the lesion, while damage to the sensory pathways causes various sensory deficits depending on which tract is affected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The corticospinal tract is the major pathway for voluntary motor control from the cerebral cortex to spinal cord motor neurones.","The corticospinal tract descends through the brainstem in the ventral portion of the pons and medullary pyramids.","The dorsal column and anterolateral pathways are sensory (afferent) rather than motor (efferent) tracts."],"references":["Natali AL, Reddy V, Bordoni B. Neuroanatomy, Corticospinal Cord Tract. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30571044","Perez MA, Cohen LG. The corticospinal system and transcranial magnetic stimulation in stroke. Top Stroke Rehabil. 2009 Jul-Aug;16(4):254-69. doi: 10.1310/tsr1604-254. PMID: 19740731; PMCID: PMC4886556.Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60119"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16374"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60119"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T23:13:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T00:02:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9065"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74625"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty